title: For Sale:  Remington 1903A3
postcontent: This is a very nice shooter grade 1903A3. The barrel is stamped 4-43, though it has undoubtedly been rearsenaled. All parts save for the magazine cutoff are parkerized. This indicates the rifle was gone over after the war, as many parts would have originally been blued. The stock, however, appears original. It shows signs of use, and the cartouches are all there that indicate originality. It really adds to the beauty and interest of the rifle. Most of the small parts are marked with an "R" as you would expect given its Remington production. Also included is a front sight cover which I believe is aftermarket (it is not a hood, just a cover for the thin front sight).Rifling is strong, bolt is smooth, and it shoots wonderfully. The rifle is fully functional, and ready to bring many more years of enjoyment.

title: For Sale:  Colt Detective Special with Factory letter C1942
postcontent: Hello, here we offer a 1942 War time colt Detective Special with a Colt factory letter. This revolver was shipped in 1942 to a gentleman in Tennessee that was a civial Flight instructor that trained WWII pilots for the War effort. This is the only reason we can figure how he was lucky enough to get a Colt shipped to him during the war. Tis is beacuse all of Colts production was shipped to the Military during these years and No civilians were allowed to get new guns because they were deemed non-essential by the Government. We did some research and came up with his story and even a picture of the man! The revolver has a bobbed hammer with a checkered top so the shooter can still cock it for single action shots. It has a Parkerized finish. The gun has very little if any use and the grips look new as well. A neat little War time Colt with a good story and a letter all in 38 special.MN buyer needs MN state photo ID and permit.Out of state buyer pays $30 shipping to thier local FFL.

title: For Sale:  Beware of seller (615) 818-3587, sells broken/non functioning items
postcontent: BEWARE OF SELLER!:REDACTED, sells broken stuff with his firearms. I traded this guy for his M&P 9 with a supposed cmr 206 laser. When i got the laser he told me the batteries were dead. He didnt give me the allen keys or have them in order to remove the small screws to change the batteries, i was told that the screw head on the screw that needs to be removed to be able to change the battery was stripped. Which means it cant be opened to chane the battery to even see if it works.i messaged back the guy to tell him and no response. He also lied about the laser being a CMR-206, after having it removed it says laserlyte on the inside. Check everything the guy tries to sell electronically or internally and make sure everything works, i gave the guy the benefit of the doubt but i guess some folks really cant be trusted. Dont buy any laser or lights from him, stay safe and buy em new. Update: i had to buy a set of allen keys to remove the back plate where the batteries where. I changed out the batteries with new ones and the laser still did not work!! He knew it was broken or didnt work and just passed it off as dead. Deal with him at your own risk if you must.
